04588nam a22006135i 9781474471596DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222000stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744715967 a10.1515/97814744715962doi  a(DE-B1597)615516  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aPepper, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Contemporary American Crime Novel :bRace, Ethnicity, Gender, Class /cAndrew Pepper. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: 'Multiculturalism is Dead! Long Live Multiculturalism!' -- t1. Making and Re-Making the American Crime Novel -- t2. 'The Unbearable Whiteness of Being': White Crime Fictthe ion in Contemporary US -- t3. 'Whose Genre is it Anyway?': Black Crime Fiction in the Contemporary US -- t4. 'The Fire this Time': Social Protest and Racial Politics- From Himes to Mosley -- t5. America's Changing Colour: Towards a Multicultural Crime Fiction -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs America's ethnic and racial character undergoes explosive transformation, its crime fictions trace, contest and celebrate the changes. The Contemporary American Crime Novel is an exciting book that offers a comprehensive overview of recent developments in American crime fiction, exploring America's dynamic, fragmented multicultural landscape and how this changing landscape has, in the process, transformed the codes and conventions of the crime novel.Mapping the genre's ideological complexities and unreconcilable tensions, its preference for uncovering, contesting and yet also reinforcing traditional relations of domination and subordination, and its vision of a morally-impaired, conflict-riven society on the verge of disintegration, The Contemporary American Crime Novel considers the emergence of African-American, female, gay, lesbian, Latino- and Asian-American crime writers alongside contemporary developments in white, male hard-boiled crime fiction. While race and ethnicity are the main focus on the book, class, gender, sexuality and region are taken into account as 'complicating factors' in the construction of identity. Authors featured include James Ellroy, James Lee Burke, Sara Paretsky, Barbara Wilson, Chester Himes, Walter Mosley, Faye Kellerman, Alex Abella and Chang-Rae Lee.Steering an informed course between the dogmas of left-wing political correctness and right-wing jingoism, the book is an engaging and accessible attempt to rescue the American crime novel from its celebrants and detractors and provide a new reading that explores the genre's growing popularity and foregrounds its ambiguities and complexities. The book will provide a lively and provocative introduction to key debates on the study of the genre, the question of multiculturalism and the theorising of race and ethnicity in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447159640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474471596423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474471596/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK